<statement>
<p>nobelium-252 has a half-life of 2.27 seconds, and its decay is modeled by <m>\displaystyle{A}={A}_{{0}}{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{2.27}}}}</m>. If the initial amount is <m>\displaystyle{A}_{{0}}={4.4}</m>, how long will it take until only one third, approximately <m>\displaystyle{A}\approx{1.5}</m> is left? <fillin characters="5" /></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>3.6</li></ul></p><p><m>\displaystyle{1.5}={4.4}{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{2.27}}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{1}}{{3}}={\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{2.27}}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{3}}\right)}}}={\left(\frac{{t}}{{2.27}}\right)}{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{3}}\right)}}}{\left({2.27}\right)}}}{{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}}}}={t}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{3.597864876637}\approx{t}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{3.6}\approx{t}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

